  abstract = {Uses a framework of comparative Marxist political economy to explore the agrarian question and agrarian transition in Prussia and the United States. Provides an account of Lenin's rendering of the Prussian and the American paths--his "capitalism from above" and "capitalism from below." Critically tests Lenin's representation of how those paths unfolded against the historical evidence. Studies the Prussian path, examining feudalism and the eve of the abolition of serfdom, and the Prussian transition and the consequences of full-blooded capitalism from above. Analyzes the American paths, discussing attempted feudalism, primitive accumulation and the eradication of native populations; slavery in the South; the transition in the postbellum South from slavery, through unfree labor, to wage labor; and the transition from early to advanced petty commodity production in the North and the West. Summarizes the results of the comparison and considers the implications for contemporary poor countries. Byres is Professor of Political Economy in the School of Oriental and African Studies at the University of London. Bibliography; authorities and subject indexes.},
  isbn = {0-312-16241-3},
  keywords = {owned}
}

