  urldate = {2021-06-04},
  abstract = {The abolition in 1990 of the estate monopoly on cultivation of burley tobacco is expected to play an important role in reducing poverty among smallholders in Malawi. A nationwide survey in 1993 shows that smallholder households cultivating burley also grow more hybrid maize, use more fertilizer, and are more food-secure. But resource-poor households—particularly those headed by women—face land and labor constraints on burley adoption. Burley and hybrid maize increase the demand for hired labor, but not enough to absorb the growth in the rural labor force. Broad-based poverty alleviation requires technology and programs targeted at the majority of smallholders with holdings of 0.5 hectares or less.},
